ScopeOfService: Transportation planning
ScopeOfWorks: Study to consider possible transport futures for Manchester and the Arc of Opportunity area, in anticipation of the influx of potentially circa 50,000 new jobs.  Such employment increase in the future will give rise to transport demands and the study considered potential transport scenarios and issues arising for both the wider Greater Manchester area and the central core area itself.  Schematic plans were produced along with coarse transport demand and capacity analysis in relation to a cordoned city centre area.  Key to the output from the work was the promotion of a change in paradigm in transport planning for the city from a 'predict and provide', demand led approach, to a 'provide and promote', supply led approach.  In this approach the determining and catalysing factor in transport and urban planning is the urban and transport quality and function that is appropriate, given the location and context followed by the promotion of sustainable and appropriate travel patterns to match the capacity and form of urban and transport townscape that is provided.  The Study culminated in the formulation of a number of specific transport planning / traffic management propositions for the central area of Manchester, and a phased list of potential transport projects.  A benchmarking exercise was undertaken early on in the Study to inform the types of transport initiatives that Manchester and Salford should aspire to, when compared to a number of European and North American cities

ScopeOfService: Structural commission: full design from feasibility to construction, plus site visits. Also Arup were appointed to produce the fire strategy for the building, and to carry out an acoustic analysis to investigate the impact of the new roof top plant on adjacent residential properties
ScopeOfWorks: Completed in May 2007, 35 Newhall Street in central Birmingham has been transformed by a £7 million refurbishment and extension. The original mid 1980’s five storey building plus single storey basement had not aged well, with small windows and an ineffective central light well resulting in poor quality office space. The only lift shaft was located at the rear of the building, and was inaccessible from the main corner entrance. The structural works added considerable value to the development by enabling a net lettable floor area of increase of around 34%, achieved by in-filling the existing light well, outward extension of the floor plates, addition of a fifth floor and new roof top plantroom. This resulted in 5,093m² net lettable grade A office space over 6 floors compared to approximately 3,800m2 before refurbishment and extension The existing structure comprised a cast in situ reinforced concrete frame on a 7.2 x 7.2m grid with a 250mm thick flat slab at each floor level. Downstand beams are generally only present at the perimeter of the building and around the edges of the internal courtyard. With the existing structure only 20 years old and in good condition, the most sustainable approach was to retain as much of the frame as possible and exploit its load capacity, whilst working within limited structural zones to achieve the proposed open plan office spaces

ScopeOfWorks:
CONFIDENTIAL PROJECT  - CONTACT BARBARA LANE BEFORE USE 
In 2004 a radio mast burnt to the ground after teenagers fired fireworks at it. The resulting fire and mast collapse onto the support building lead to significant financial loss (both capital and customer) for National Grid Wireless (NGW) who owned the building. The result of this fire was a thorough investigation into the factors that contributed to the fire growth from the initial firework, why it spread so fast and what the resulting mechanisms were that lead to the mast collapse. Once this information was provided to NGW, they were interested in determining if additional protection could be included on their existing mast portfolio, and potential new constructions, to reduce the risk of this loss occurring again. Loss included their service to customers, many of whom permanently left as a result, as well as replacement of the mast and all systems operating to it, temporary service provision for customers who remained;plus loss of profile in the public domain

ScopeOfService: Civil, structural, geotechnical, ground remediation, transportation, mechanical, electrical (including specialist communications and security), environmental, acoustic and fire engineering design services. Key aspects of our service on this project addressed the re-use of an existing industrial site. This included remediation of contamination, sustainable drainage and the provision of new access roads and off-site highway improvements. Particular attention was paid to increasing the use of natural light and ventilation
ScopeOfWorks:
CONFIDENTIAL JOB 
The prison was built as an entirely new facility, to provide secure accommodation for 800 male prisoners in 700 cells. The prison is located mid-way between Glasgow and Edinburgh, adjacent to Addiewell Station. The site was former industrial premises, with a long history of mineral workings, paraffin extraction and concrete product manufacture. It was significantly contaminated and presented difficult ground conditions. Bio-remediation was used to clear hydro-carbons, mine shafts were grouted and piled foundations used extensively. The new prison achieves high design and visual standards and the design was developed to be space-efficient and operationally-led in conjunction with our architect, contractor and operator team partners. The buildings comprise two four-storey house blocks, creating sixteen operational units, together with an entry building and a large central-support complex. The house blocks were of precast concrete construction, with in situ concrete hubs; the remaining buildings have steel-framed superstructures. The entry building develops from our experience gained on Forest Bank, Peterborough and Bronzefield prisons and includes the visits, administration, gatehouse and staff training functions of the prison. The central-support complex houses catering, medical, sports, teaching and worship spaces. The site required extensive external works, including a new access road, off-site highway improvements, significant areas of car park and sustainable drainage installations to the satisfaction of SEPA. The energy centre and plant compound are located within the 5.2m high secure prison perimeter

ScopeOfWorks: These two projects brought together the College’s 7,000 students into a single new Campus at Swanswell from its previous homes at the Butts, Tile Hill and Maxwell Centres. The move was part of the biggest urban regeneration project in Coventry since the end of the war. Phase 1 of the project included facilities for teaching construction, vehicle engineering and general engineering workshops; telecoms, electronics, computing, music and multi-media classrooms and recording studio as well as demonstration and multipurpose rooms. Phase 2 of the new campus includes 11,400m² of teaching accommodation for performing arts, hair and beauty teaching and sports facilities. Development of both phases was constrained by many of the factors found on inner city sites such as restricted space, difficulties for deliveries, poor perimeter air quality and high external noise levels, presence of utilities and rights of way across the site, complex site development history with associated uncertainties about below-ground obstructions, boundary issues and potential for unexploded ordnance. There was also a difference in ground level of about ten metres across the site which provided significant vehicle access and engineering design challenges. The College was committed to the philosophy of partnering and opted for a two-stage design and build NEC contract. The Contractor was appointed at RIBA Stage C and contributed to the development of the final scheme.

JobNameLong: UNIVERSTIY OF BIRMINGHAM GISBERT KAPP AND METALLURGY & MATER
ScopeOfService: Structural feasibility of options for new glazed entrances, detailed structural design of chosen option for glazed entrances, structural input and design for refurbishment as required. Engineering design through to construction.
ScopeOfWorks: Refurbishment and backlog maintenance of fabric and infrastructure, plus construction of new glazed entrances for both Gisbert Kapp and Metallurgy & Materials Buildings. The existing six storey structure was built circa 1966 and comprises a steel frame with a 5” thick composite precast / in situ slab. The columns and perimeter beams to the steel frame are concrete encased. The building has a central in situ concrete lift and stair core, and in situ concrete stair cores at either end of the building; these elements provide lateral stability to the frame. Outside the main entrance to the building is an in situ concrete podium structure beneath the main lecture theatre structure, which comprises a reinforced concrete frame with a ribbed slab, the soffit of which is exposed. A reinforced concrete bridge structure (footbridge no. 2) links the podium area to an adjacent single storey concrete car park structure, and is currently the main pedestrian route into the building. Foundations to the building are reinforced concrete pads bearing on to medium dense sands. All information regarding the existing structure was taken from archive drawings by Concrete (Midlands) Limited, and Botteley & Chaffer Consulting Engineers, and has been subject to confirmation during the works being carried out on site. The refurbishment of the Gisbert Kapp was carried out in a series of 4 contracts, whilst the building is still occupied. A majority of the refurbishment involved replacement of mechanical and electrical systems and remodelling / redecoration to internal spaces. The structural works were generally small scale and in isolated locations, rather than building-wide. Structural works briefly comprise the following:  Replacement of mechanical and electrical systems and plant including creation of new risers to accommodate these services;  Replacement of blast vent covers within the floor slab of laboratories and classrooms;  Construction of a new anechoic chamber in an existing switchgear and store room at sixth floor;  Construction of a new stair from lower ground level to second floor to improve access to lecture theatres;  Creation of new enclosed entrance and reception area on existing external podium structure beneath the main lecture theatre, including the in-fill of existing steps to the east side of the podium to create greater useable space;  Construction of a new single storey steel frame entrance structure to the east side of the podium structure;  Construction of a new canopy over the existing footbridge entrance to the building;  Construction of a new steel footbridge from Pritchatts Road to the existing raised car park deck at the front of the building.

The college development opened to students at the start of the academic year 2009. The simultaneous construction of four academic buildings began in early 2009, providing around 24,000m² of accommodation for the School of Law, School of Management, Department of Computer Science, Department of Theatre Film and Television, and a landmark academic Hub building as a focal point for campus orientation. A further building was added to the simultaneous construction sequence in late 2009, to provide 3,000m² of flexible lettable office space for enterprise collaboration between departments and fledgling businesses, as part of the University innovation and knowledge transfer strategy. Energy work included supporting the University in a successful application for funding to install a biomass CHP plant, serving the extended district heating and electrical HV network. BREEAM assessment has been undertaken for all projects at design and construction stages, and all currently indicate a ‘Very Good’ rating. Handover of the academic buildings began in August, and will be complete in October 2010, at the rate of one building every two weeks. The overall construction programme of around 26 months from green-field to fully occupied has delivered buildings of around £105M construction value, an average investment rate in excess of £4M/month, with Arup involvement at every stage.

ScopeOfService: Civil, structural, geotechnic, ground remediation, mechanical, electrical - including specialist security and communications, environmental, sustainability, acoustic and fire engineering design services. 2007 to 2010. Key aspects of our service addressed the construction of an entire new stand-alone 480-cell prison within the secure wall of an existing live establishment. These included difficult ground conditions requiring fully-piled foundations.
ScopeOfWorks: Working under the Ministry of Justice Strategic Alliance Framework, the HMP YOI Isis development comprises a new standalone 480 place training prison for young adult males, designed to Category B standards. Constructed on the site of under-used land within the existing Category A HMP Belmarsh prison perimeter wall, a series of coordinated ‘site secure’ enabling works contracts ensured the ongoing function and security of the existing establishment during the build. The enabling works comprised the construction of a high security perimeter dividing fence, constructed to separate the main site for the HMP YOI Isis development from the original HMP Belmarsh. Also included in the enabling works were the demolition and replacement of a dog unit (kennels, grooming shed and handlers accommodation), constructed outside of the secure perimeter, farms and gardens (staff and prisoner changing, rest rooms, admin and stores) and a sports facility (all weather pitch, staff and prisoner changing, stores classroom and admin) all within a secure compound, built inside the existing HMP Belmarsh Category A prison on vacant land. Accommodation for the new prison within the secured perimeter provides: two 3-storey houseblocks, with galleried wings and central galleried atrium hub, incorporating an induction facility. Entry building: incorporating staff lockers, a visitor reception area, gate lodge, visits areas, video courts and stores. Central building comprising an educational ‘academy’ of workshops, classroom and library facilities. The central catering facility, healthcare and a multi-faith worship centre, 2 storey sports, gymnasium and staff training/cafeteria facility and adjoining separation and care facility. Secure external works include all weather sports pitches, exercise yards with equipment, hard landscaped courtyards and planted areas and a secure covered walkway ‘street’. External works outside of the secure perimeter comprise access road, pedestrian and cycle ways, visitors car park, vehicular security barriers, staff parking, bicycle parking, hard landscaped and planted areas, including wetland to meet planning conditions relating to ecological enhancement measures and an energy centre incorporating a biomass boiler, combined heat and power (CHP) plant and traditional gas fired boilers. The prison has been designed to create an internal environment that has intrinsic therapeutic value. Access to landscaped external spaces, maximising the amount of naturally lit and ventilated spaces and the provision of views to active external spaces all contribute to the creation of a positive internal environment in which to live and work. The facility is designed to achieve BREEAM Excellent rating. This resulted in the development of a low energy, low carbon design (for example, a 56% carbon saving is achieved in the accommodation buildings compared to 2002 levels) employing a variety of measures such as the provision of improved building fabric (insulation and infiltration), low energy lighting with automatic lighting control, increased opportunity for use of natural light and ventilation, low energy mechanical ventilation systems with heat recovery, CHP and biomass heating plant. In addition, rainwater harvesting systems have been provided. In our design solution, working alongside our architect and contractor partners from the outset, we developed and integrated system building techniques to reduce programme and timescales, improve efficiencies in construction and create greater cost certainty for our client and the prison operators.

ScopeOfWorks:
This major city centre redevelopment is part of Birmingham’s Big City Plan and will enable circa 
1.8 million ft2 of offices, shops, leisure and cultural facilities together with civic amenities, a hotel and new public realm.

Paradise Circus is one of the most prominent and historic parts of Birmingham city centre and is home to the Central Library, Birmingham Library Theatre and Paradise Forum. The first phase of the scheme will include a revised road layout, substantial new public space and provide 350,000 ft2 of Grade A office space. 

Our initial involvement was to provide engineering and specialist input into feasibility studies and masterplans for the ambitious proposals. Outline planning was granted in December 2012 and in May 2014 we completed the Employer’s Requirements documentation for Phase 1, a large enabling works package. 

This first phase comprises major re-modelling of the site to incorporate car parking provision beneath a new podium deck, new access arrangements and significant services diversions and utilities upgrades. The constrained site is immensely complex to ‘unlock’, not least due to the A38 dual carriageway tunnels passing beneath the site. 

We are now providing all engineering disciplines for the design of the first two buildings for the site, in partnership with Glenn Howells Architects and Eric Parry Architects. This includes providing carbon modelling, fire engineering and wind engineering. We have also been appointed to prepare the Employer’s Information Requirements for the development and the BIM Execution Plan for the buildings with an ongoing role as Argent’s Information Manager. 

Due for completion in 2018, the two buildings will complete Chamberlain Square and will serve as a catalyst for the rest of the development.

ScopeOfService: Civil, structural, geotechnic, ground remediation, mechanical, electrical (including specialist security and communications), environmental, sustainability, acoustic and fire engineering design services. 1997 to 2000 and then 2007 to 2009. In the original project key aspects included the re-use of existing power station site, including foundations. This project was our first to develop precast concrete volumetric cell units - subsequently used on all projects. We also pioneered prefabrication of cell duct risers, subsequently used on all projects. Sustainable drainage and fire engineered solution to smoke ventilation were innovative. For the recent extension, solutions were required to permit construction of a new house-block and extension to the secure entry building on a live prison site. A realigned prison secure wall formed the key to this solution. Fully precast cell units and hub were used for the first time in the PPP environment. A BREEAM very good rating has been achieved by employing a variety of measures including the provision of improved building fabric (insulation and infiltration), low energy lighting with automatic lighting control, increased opportunity for use of natural light and ventilation, low energy mechanical ventilation systems with heat recovery, combined heat and power (CHP) and high efficiency heating plant.
ScopeOfWorks:
CONFIDENTIAL JOB 
Arup has been involved in both phases of development of this prison – the original build (opened in 2000) and the extension (completed in 2009). This was the first prison to be designed and constructed by our custodial consortia group with Kalyx (then UKDS) and Interserve (then Tilbury Douglas). The prison was constructed on a demolished power station and includes the regeneration and redevelopment of a substantial area in the Greenbelt adjacent to the River Irwell and the Salford Canal site. The custodial facilities initially included 6 no. 4-storey House Blocks, providing approximately 1100 prisoner spaces in 800 cells, together with Industrial Training Units, an Education Wing, Sports Hall, Chapel, Medical, Separation and Catering Facilities. The Entry Complex, where the visits centre, admissions and the gatehouse combine into one building forms part of the secure perimeter. By adopting a compact and effective layout incorporating precast concrete cell units it was possible to size the prison within the 14m residential height limit outlined in the planning brief. This had the advantage of reducing site take up and relieving the planning restrictions, creating a further green area adjacent to the river. This in turn reduced the visual impact of the prison. The recent Category B extension involved a new four-storey cell block, accommodating 264 prisoners in 230 cells. The Entry Building was also extended providing enhanced visitors areas / staff training and administrative space. The All Weather Sports area was extended and there is additional landscaping works within the prison. External works modifications (including new car-parking to replace that lost beneath the new house-block) are also incorporated. The layout was guided by the planning limitations of the available site area and extends the perimeter without reducing the available public open space. The location of the buildings is such that the existing secure perimeter of the prison remained unaffected during the house block construction and was connected on completion thus maintaining maximum security throughout.

JobNameLong: DEVELOPMENT OF SURFACE WATER MANAGEMENT POLICY & PLAN FOR RO
ScopeOfService: Hydrology analysis, hydraulics, flood hazard mapping, existing structures surveys, LiDAR survey, consultation with key stakeholders, building an integrated model of the catchment, problem identification, option appraisal and production of a flood risk assessment report relating to the preferred options together with a surface water management plan report that included detailed flood hazard maps and a proposed draft developers guide to sustainable urban drainage systems.
ScopeOfWorks: Development of a surface water management policy and plan for Mullingar in Southern Ireland. The scope of the commission was to consider the impact of the new development on the existing system that flows through the town and to produce a storm water policy for the town. To allow the surface water from the new development to be fully considered, an integrated model of the whole catchment was built. This model included the sewer system, including CSOs and combined pumping stations, the river network and a digital ground model of the surface. The model was created in a prototype version of a commercial drainage simulation package that allowed all the elements of the model to be dynamically interactive allowing the water to flow into and out of each part of the system. This was used to produce a flood risk assessment for the whole development area (2 km²) that included provisional solutions for all the deficiencies within the system that had been identified by the model. A surface water management plan (SWMP) was also included that produced flood hazard maps for Robinstown and Irishtown, which are the areas that are to be developed.

JobNameLong: UNIVERSITY OF WARWICK - CHEMISTRY & PHYSICS LAB
ScopeOfService: Civil, structural and fire input to design from scheme to RIBA stage E. Arup Acoustics and AT&R also have separate commission to undertake detailed study of the vibrations associated with the very sensitive equipment.
ScopeOfWorks:
The Materials & Analytical Sciences Building was designed to provide a world class facility to support the research of the scientists at the University of Warwick. The five-storey, 4,699m2 building comprises laboratories, meeting rooms and office space and incorporates a new main entrance, reception and concourse space. The building was designed to encourage interaction between physicists and chemists by putting its ‘science on show’ in an open plan rectilinear block with four floors of laboratory and office space, below which sits a double height laboratory space for high specification research instrumentation. A single storey curving ‘serpentine wall’ houses an electron microscopy suite which was required to be detached from the main build in order to minimise vibrations. A significant double-height, densely-used roof-top plant room completed the accommodation. 

All elements of structure were considered in detail, not only with the University and architect to ensure that the required spaces and facilities could be provided in a safe and economic manner, but also with the Mechanical, Electrical & Public Health designers to integrate with their complex and extensive installations and also with the contractor, to maximise buildability and bring further economies based upon their supply-chain input. For example, the entire superstructure was developed with steel-framed and concrete framed options, which was gradually refined to be largely concrete-framed, including post-tensioned, precast and normally-reinforced elements but retaining steelwork above the plantroom level. For substructures piled and ground-supported options were developed in detail, allowing the contractor to select the most economic solution for construction. The advantage of the two-stage design and build tender was that the University benefitted from this close working and the savings accrued to their project. The economy results both from simple cost and programme considerations and overall the optimum cost and time solution was obtained, whilst keeping to the original high design standards. 

Of technical interest, a number of examples are associated with services, for example the substantial roof-mounted extract flues, requiring carefully detailed structural support. Of particular significance however are the massive foundations for the specialised microscopy suite and mass spectrometer suite. Our engineers worked closely with our acousticians to analyse and design the concrete structure to comply with stringent movement and vibration criteria. A key aspect of our solution was to isolate these extremely sensitive pieces of equipment from the main part of the building frame and ground-borne vibrations through careful detailing of the structure. We also took great efforts to design links at high level into an existing building that minimised impact upon the occupants. 

The site was tightly fitted adjacent to existing University facilities, so the civil engineering design also presented challenges. Access roads and gas-storage areas were designed in a very compact arrangement, with minimum space take permitted from retaining walls, leading to a piled solution being adopted to minimise excavation and road-closure. Sustainable drainage had to be designed to strictly limit flows into the existing ‘almost at capacity’ foul and storm water sewers and we had to deal with rainfall intensities making allowance for future climate change. Using a combination of storage devices and over-sized pipes, together with flow-control devices, we managed to design to meet all criteria; carefully integrating the drainage with the building substructures and external civils elements. Ultimately our designs helped the building achieve a BREEAM Excellent rating and an EPC rating of A. 

Project value: £24m

ScopeOfService: Support to developers bid, may include geotechnical , utilities, transport and sustainability. Arup designed the contiguous piled wall and capping beam along one edge of the site, with a further contiguous piled wall adjacent to a nearby existing building as part of the enabling works. The piled wall allowed the part-basement to be constructed in one of the new buildings, and minimises the risk of instability of the surrounding landscaping or undermining of the existing building. The capping beam has been designed with pull-out reinforcement bars where possible. These are a structural requirement to form continuity with the connecting elements, but by using pull out bars rather than projecting straight bars the risk of injury to site workers is minimised. The public realm between the two new buildings also acts as a service distribution corridor. Arup carried out detailed risk assessment to review the buildability of the new services and the interfaces with easements for gas, electricity and telecommunications services running throught the site. The construction of the service corridor and the adjacent retaining walls, which form the edges of the buildings, has been considered from a health and safety perspective. Arup designed and coordinated the ducts for the incoming High Voltage and Low Voltage supply, telecommunications network for BT, Virgin Media, Stoke-on-Trent private communications network, a site wide estate management communications system, foul and surface drainage systems, gas and water supplies. These services were designed to allow future phases in the masterplan to be constructed without disruption to the Phase 1 public realm works. The retaining walls and service corridor have been arranged such that they can be constructed in an open excavation with battered slopes, whilst maintaining a sufficiently wide strip of ground between them to build the service corridor. This allows for both standard methods of construction and physical separation of the site activities, therefore reducing the risks associated with construction below ground.
ScopeOfWorks: Competition to be preferred developer for a new central business district (CBD) for Stoke on Trent. Stoke-on-Trent Central Business District includes two new office buildings to be occupied by Stoke-on-Trent City Council, as part of a wider masterplan to redevelop an area of the city centre. Arup designed the enabling works for the masterplan and the engineering services for Phase 1 which involves two office buildings 20000m² GIA and the public realm. Arup has provided the Civil, Structural, Mechanical, Electrical, Fire and Public Health Engineering Services on the project. The site previously included residential and commercial buildings which were demolished as part of the enabling works. Arup design includes site clearance, demolition, removal of obstructions, capping to mine shafts, coal seam treatment, sitewide earthworks, remediation, utilities and drainage diversions and retaining structures. Arup managed all the interfaces with utility companies including BT, Virgin Media, Cable & Wireless, Western Power, National Grid, Severn Trent and Stoke Council’s Highways department to ensure all their assets were either diverted or decommissioned if no longer required. As part of these works, Arup was instrumental in agreeing easements with National Grid, Severn Trent and Western Power for retained assets. Arup produced a comprehensive utilities handover document which was used by both the enabling works contractor and Phase 1 building contractor to manage the remaining utilities assets and easements.

ScopeOfService: Sustainable buildings advice relating to carbon emissions and energy procurement.
ScopeOfWorks:
Following the successful launch of the first Arup LSC Zero Carbon Colleges report in the summer of 2008, we were commissioned to develop the recommendations with further investigations into the emissions of the Further Education capital estate. The scope was expanded to include emissions from existing colleges and how they can be reduced through operational improvements and behavioural changes. Arup’s scope was sustainability advice. The clients objective was the development of a robust policy framework that would allow them to meet their target of all new colleges being zero carbon from 2016. 

Innovation was shown by the proposing of a robust trajectory towards zero carbon based on continued reduction of allowable Energy Performance Certificate rating for colleges accessing Learning and Skills Council (LSC) funding along with the setting up of zero carbon pilot projects and placing increasing emphasis on sustainability in the procurement process. Emissions reductions though behavioural change was also investigated, with a successful workshop being run at a college involving the leadership team, support and teaching staff and students. 

The work involved the LSC convening the Zero Carbon Colleges Working Group of which Arup were a key member, providing engineering and sustainability research. The Working Group brought together people from all disciplines involved in further education college design such as architects, developers, college principals and funding body members.

From our experience at Heslington East:

- The NEC requires timely management of information flow.
- The construction programme must allocate adequate periods for testing, commissioning and defects rectification.
- It is essential to monitor and report on the contractor’s testing and commissioning activities against this programme.
- The Client should consider retaining float in their handover and fit-out programme.

As well as providing contemporary office space and helping to breathe new life into Stafford Town Centre, the Council estimates that the move will result in enormous savings to the Borough; not least in reducing its escalating energy costs. The 135,000 sq ft bespoke development is split across two buildings linked by a new town square with the ground floor incorporating a mix of retail and leisure uses. Sustainability and future proofing were fundamental design considerations for the team; all within a constrained budget. From a structural standpoint, our response is an excellently engineered reinforced concrete ‘flat slab’ frame. This solution not only contributes to the environmental strategy, by providing significant thermal mass, but also forms part of the internal aesthetic. The office floor spaces have high quality exposed concrete soffits, detailed in a manner to give the impression of being jointed, through a regular pattern of recesses. Such a feature would generally impair the fire integrity of the slab by reducing the cover (protection under fire) to the reinforcement. However, our fire engineers modelled the performance of the slab under a fire simulation and demonstrated that the recesses do not impair the slab’s integrity. Consequently, we were able to provide the feature soffit without any additional cost to the frame and to the satisfaction of the Fire Officer. Flexibility in use was key to assuring adequate future proofing. To achieve this cost effectively, we undertook detailed finite element analyses of all the floor plates to optimise their load capacity for a given depth, resulting in an estimated saving of 25mm slab depth of concrete per floor, which also saved on foundation costs. The building achieved a BREEAM ‘Excellent’ rating and an EPC Rating ‘A’.

The site is circa 10 hectares, and provides an educational space for approximately 1550 pupils. The facility combines three existing schools White heath, Westminster and St Michaels, and provides central recreation and sports facilities. The schools are separated within the facility due to the different social and educational needs of the students. The new facility is built on an exposed hillside site north of Rowley village, previously mined and occupied by Rowley College. The site is considerably sloped and a programme of earthworks was undertaken to provide a more suitable formation for the facility, the cut and fill was up to plus and minus 2.5m. The building is founded on dolerite rock, the depth of which this is found varies across the site up to 5m below current ground level. The foundation solution represented this by the combination of concrete pads, driven steel piles and a concrete raft. The building is a combination of steel and concrete frames, to suit the construction programme, structural spans and mechanical requirements. Precast lift cores were also incorporated. The building is required to meet BREEAM 2006 Excellent, and houses a 700kW biomass boiler and a 1330m3 attenuation tank. External works include multi-use games areas for tennis and basketball etc, football, cricket and athletics pitches, and an all weather sports pitch. Car parks and a road structure were also included. Part of the highways work included an S38/278 works agreement for a new junction and connection into the existing Hawes lane.

ScopeOfWorks:
Doncaster Performance Venue, Waterdale.

Arup were involved in the development of a Civic/Cultural Quarter in Doncaster from the bid stages in 2005. As part of this development a new state-of-the-art performance venue was developed providing a new dynamic performing arts centre. As in any multiuse facility, the challenge is to allow as many creative activities to happen at the same time without causing a disturbance to each other. The design team’s response was to provide a venue that can accommodate up-to 1250 visitors across a number of specially designed spaces.
It includes a 600 seat auditorium, “black box” style flexible performance space (200 seating or 400 standing), dance and drama studios, teaching facilities and a café bar. 

The main lyric theatre is designed to be a highly intimate space, optimised for hosting amplified touring shows. It is a dense concrete construction and includes stalls and circle seating with a 25m fly tower over the stage, stair and lift access is provided to the various levels. The auditorium is supported by a number of technical spaces; follow spots, lighting bridges, sound desk and control room. It includes an orchestra pit with removable rostra to facilitate additional seating, designed to allow the addition of a full orchestra pit lift at a future date. Removable rostra enable alternative locations for the sound desk. Duct routes are provided to facilitate outside broadcasting. A number of modes of operation were established to enable various uses; orchestra/additional seating, stalls only / full auditorium, rehearsal/performance. Support accommodation includes a workshop and props stores below the stage area, with a trap door from the stage. A scene dock enables level delivery from the delivery bay to the stage and a space for scenes to be created. A raised loading bay with dock levellers provides access for two delivery lorries. 

The “black box” space is a ‘box-in-box’ construction and incorporates a technical grid at high level and a balcony level. The dance and drama studio incorporate winched technical grids. 

The performance spaces are supported by a range of back of house spaces; dressing rooms, green room, stage door, offices, laundry and wardrobe rooms, front of house spaces include: café/bar, prep kitchen, beer store, box office and cloakrooms. The education space includes a moveable acoustic partition, so that it can be used as a single or two spaces and also as additional foyer or dressing room spaces. The building incorporates a front of house passenger list and a back of house goods/passenger lift. 

The site required a large number of utility diversions to be undertaken to facilitate the project. The building faces on to a new Civic square with hard landscaping, water and lighting features. 

Arup’s strategy for the building utilised natural ventilation wherever possible within the constraints of the high performance acoustic and environmental demands of the theatre spaces. The performance spaces are mechanically ventilated but highly efficient systems were incorporated to minimise the energy in use. 

The environmental solutions incorporate the use of CHP to reduce carbon emissions and heat recovery, assisting the project to achieve BREEAM Very Good.

ScopeOfService: Eternal fire spread study to include preparation of a report detailing the external fire spread analysis for each facade of the building.  The report will use the following process to assess the degree of protection to the facades; Clearly define the notional boundaries for each facade. Use the ‘enclosing rectangles’ approach described in BR187 External fire spread; As necessary, 3D radiation modelling of the façade using thermal radiation analysis (TRA) software will be carried out. This provides a more precise application of the scientific principles behind the BRE method to allow for the areas of louvers and glazing to be modelled and the resulting radiation calculated.  Assessment of the degree of fire loading and likely design fire sizes within the building can also be used. The BRE method assumes that the entire fire compartment is simultaneously at post flashover fire conditions. Given the nature of the buildings this may be a conservative estimate.  Assess the acceptance criteria within BR187 against the specific site conditions. This may result in the 12.6kW/m² received radiation criteria in that document being concluded to be conservative.

ScopeOfWorks: Major refurbishment of the Great Hall at the National Railway Museum, York. The National Railway Museum currently experiences 800,000 visitors per year to a site that has two major halls separated by a public road, with two main entrances.  The purpose of the project is to increase visitor numbers to over one million by creating a unified entrance, providing a link bridge over the road, refreshing the exhibition space and significantly improving the narrative experience by introducing a high level walkway through the Great Hall. Creating the appropriate environment for up to 4000 visitors while maintaining the exacting criteria required for the individual museum exhibits in a hall that is circa 120 metres by 60 metres with a height of up to 20 metres has been the greatest challenge. The Great Hall project was unfortunately put on hold in 2011 due to funding issues, however Arup have continued to work with the National Railway Museum, providing advice on their electrical and CCTV infrastructure as well as detailed design for elements of the Station Hall refurbishment and the creation of a new entrance, foyer and shop.

JobNameLong: SHEFFIELD HALLAM UNIVERSITY - CHARLES STREET DEVELOPMENT
ScopeOfService:
Provision of a series of fully annotated drawings and sketches to assist the lead designer in understanding the fire safety provisions required for the design. We will also outline different design options and provide a commentary on the pro’s and con’s of each option and areas where fire engineering can provide added value. These annotated drawings will then be used as a vehicle to enable the fire strategy to be defined at the earliest opportunity. We would also undertake initial discussions with the approval bodies to reduce and manage any perceived ‘approvals risks’ relating to the fire safety design. An outline fire strategy report would be prepared to provide a summary of the key fire safety measures and proposed approach.
The principles of the Outline Fire Safety Strategy will be further developed to provide a full and concise explanation of the fire safety requirements for the building. It will establish the fire safety design criteria and provide an explanation of any alternative approaches to be adopted. A detailed fire strategy report will be produced for this stage. The primary aim of this report will be to assist the design team in gaining Building Regulation Approval for the fire safety aspects of the design.

ScopeOfService: Arup is providing a professional team including all of the services required to progress the design of the National Training Centre from the existing RIBA Stage C point through to Stage L.
ScopeOfWorks: Officially opened in March 2013 by acclaimed musician Jools Holland, The Backstage Centre provides state-of-the-art training facilities for the fast-growing industries of live music and theatre events production. As part of the High House Production Park, The Backstage Centre contributes to a regeneration programme that is enhancing the viability and vitality of the area. This BREEAM “Excellent” building provides training in technical and backstage skills that simply aren’t available elsewhere, either locally or nationally, and is a major focus of creative development, enterprise and learning. The centre offers a fully equipped space for all types of production rehearsal and training – including large-scale staging and real-time technical training with arena-scale live bands. It gives students the opportunity to learn in a number of different contexts, in particular alongside world class performers and top backstage professionals. We provided the National Skills Academy with a ‘one-stop-shop’ service from briefing through to commissioning and handover. Our engineers drew on their considerable experience of designing arena and other performing arts venues in defining and detailing the heavily serviced sound stage area. Our rail engineers assisted in obtaining approval from Network Rail for constructing adjacent High Speed 1. Our acousticians advised on acoustic isolation requirements as well as specifying the detailed requirements for rehearsal rooms and recording studios. Our project team delivered on the National Skills Academy’s aspirations for an inspirational building that provides a first class learning environment for those in the industry, whilst also promoting local regeneration. We worked with a diverse range of building users comprising experts in the theatre, music and live events industries, to shape the brief and complete the timely construction of this full-scale venue.

JobNameLong: RISK MAPPING WEST YORKSHIRE FIRE & RESCUE SERVICE
ScopeOfService:
Close collaboration between WYFRS and Arup will be needed to ensure that the developing methodology provides the necessary output. Hence the following approach is proposed: 
Review the risk indicators and sample data sets provided by WYFRS and provide a qualitative screening of the risk indicators to identify primary, secondary and tertiary factors. 
Hold a workshop with WYFRS representatives to discuss the initial screening exercise and to define the approach. 
Undertake a simple quantitative screening exercise to develop a combined risk rating for sample station areas.  This will consist of completing the risk scoring exercise for three or four specific stations to test the range of scoring and whether the Total Risk Score is commensurate with the typical risk expected for a certain area i.e. Leeds and Bradford would be expected to be higher risk than Otley and Meltham.
A further workshop will be held with WYFRS to discuss the outcome of the screening exercise, before completing the more detailed exercise for all station areas.
Arup will provide a concise report to explain the rationale behind both the qualitative and semi-quantitative approach to risk indicator weighting that is used to determine the overall risk rating. The appropriate report format will be developed as the exercise is progressed.
The process for validation will include close collaboration between WYFRS and Arup. Arup will require the Fire Service to provide details on government directives and Fire Service targets to ascertain the key objectives and priorities to be used as a basis for risk ratings. 
Screening exercises will be completed for certain stations to ascertain whether the Total Risk Score reflects the typical level of risk expected for a certain station area i.e. Leeds is expected to be high, Otley is expected to be low. WYFRS will be asked to appraise the initial findings of the screening exercises as part of the process.
Sensitivity of the overall ratings to individual risk indicators will be investigated to ensure that risk ratings are not overly sensitive to small changes in discrete areas, but retain enough sensitivity to be used as a measure of progress over time.
ScopeOfWorks:
WYFRS is developing an approach to identify the risks associated with each station area. This information will be of assistance in a number of areas such as: Assessing the resources required for each station area; Providing a means to measure progress of station areas in reducing risk levels; Providing a means to identify where resources can be best targeted in each station area. To date, WYFRS has identified a number of ‘risk indicators’ for a wide range of factors, based on fire service and government data. The next step in the process aims to combine the different risk indicators together, to determine an overall risk rating for each station area, thereby allowing a risk map of West Yorkshire to be formed. WYFRS has requested assistance from Arup Fire to identify a methodology for combining the risk indicators and validating the risk process. The process will include: Review and comment on the validity of the Risk Indicators identified by WYFRSReview and comment on the statistical data and criteria process for risk indicators.
Guidance on methodology for setting parameters.
Methodology for aggregating risk indicators to give overall risk ratings.
Interaction between risk indicators: If two risk indicators reflect the same or similar risks, then the approach would need to take account of this to avoid ‘double counting’ in the overall risk rating.
Weighting of risks: e.g. indicators that mainly reflect life safety risk would typically have a higher weighting that indicators that mainly reflect property protection.

JobNameLong: THE BRITISH LIBRARY MEANS OF ESCAPE ASSESSMENT
ScopeOfService:
Carry out an engineering assessment of the library, its use and existing escape capacity, and provide guidance on a new maximum occupancy, and importantly, its distribution within specific zones defined by the British Library, from the lower ground level to level 6, inclusive. Our assessment also includes the exhibition gallery and the conference centre. 

The assessment of means of escape is expected to enable a greater number of occupants to be present in the building, without actually changing the physical building fabric in any way.  This will mean that the British Library will be able to consolidate their existing staff more efficiently and potentially sublet subsequent disused areas to other organisations.
ScopeOfWorks:
The British Library consists of east and west wings linked by a central block which includes a large front entrance. These three distinct areas are fire separated to allow for currently independent evacuation areas and for people to escape from one block into another before making their way to the final exit. 

There is a mix of public and staff throughout the library.  There is no access by the public to staff-only regions during day to day operations.  This access is restricted by a combination of access controlled doors and management procedures.  However, in the event of an emergency, a selection of these control measures are altered.  This includes release of some access control doors and fire marshalling of other specific routes, to encourage members of the public to egress via all potentially available stairs.

ScopeOfWorks: Kirkgate Market is a key anchor tenant to the Kirkgate shopping centre, Bradford, and was built in 1974. The market comprises of 184 stalls, 44 storage rooms, offices, toilet facilities and an underground unloading area. Bradford Metropolitan District Council (BMDC) occupy the market on an under lease from the head landlord, Prudential Assurance Company Ltd, on a peppercorn rent for a term of 125 years from the 1st of January. The BMDC is a tenant to the Head Landlord, but also the landlord for various tenants that currently occupy the market stalls. These leases are individual 6 year occupational leases. The leases, however, expired on the 1st of April, 2002, and the tenants are currently holding on from renewing on these terms. The market has been affected by the decline in non-food sales over the past 3 years, and competition from major low value retailers within the city centre. There is an increasing trend showing a reducing footfall and an increase in unit vacancies within the Market. BMDC have commissioned a design team to explore solutions to this problem in a bid to entice new trade to the market and prevent its steady decline. The design team includes an architect, quantity surveyor, building services engineers and potentially structural engineers.

ScopeOfWorks: As part of a major capital works programme, the University of Birmingham is developing a new indoor sports facility on a site at a main access point to its Edgbaston campus. As well as creating state of the art facilities, the building sits in a landscaped setting, defining new pedestrian access to the University. The facilities will include the first regional 50m swimming pool with moveable floor and boom in addition to activity rooms, gym, spa, climbing wall, squash and badminton courts. The brownfield site has set many challenges for the design team. Working closely with the architect we have helped to develop a building form that responds to the significant level changes across the site whilst maintaining permeability for pedestrians through the site. The site is located on a major geological fault which has resulted in contrasting ground conditions on either side of the fault line. After analysing this in detail, we developed bespoke foundation solutions for different parts of the structure depending on where they lie, relative to the fault. We have provided a structural solution that responds to setting; functional in the multi-purpose sports hall, simple elegance in the pool hall with its large span ‘glulam’ timber roof, through to the feature colonnade in high quality pre-cast concrete. Construction value = £37 milllion

ScopeOfWorks: In response to the new Government targets for reducing the construction cost of new schools, we were approached by Interserve to help develop a truly innovative concept for the development of new schools. The resulting Podsolve concept gives significant savings in time and budget (a third less than traditional build schools), and provides the added benefits of being highly flexible in-use. At the heart of the concept is a fully modular classroom with the minimum of external services connections to increase its potential re-configurability to adapt to changing educational needs. The classrooms are naturally ventilated via a unique ventilator conceived and designed by us. This ensures appropriate acoustic performance is achieved whilst maintaining high levels of air-flow to keep the classrooms well ventilated and at an appropriate temperature throughout the year. In 2011, Interserve was invited to submit proposals for the redevelopment of Parklands Academy in Leeds. The options available for the re-development of the school were extremely limited due to the budget being significantly reduced. It appeared that only a partial refurbishment of the school (a ‘clasp’ school in a significant state of disrepair) over a very extended programme would meet the strict affordability criteria. However, through utilising the Podsolve concept, Interserve was able to provide a brand new school that fell within the very tight budget constraints. E-ACT Leeds East Academy opened its doors to students in the Spring of 2013. £13.65m construction value.

ScopeOfWorks: Demolition of an existing building, dating from 1966 and built over the Waterloo and City, Northern and Bakerloo London Underground tunnels and construction of a new office building on the same site, located in Lambeth, central London. The building will consist of up to 39 storeys above ground, limited by the Somerset House / St. James’s Park viewing corridor and potentially deep basements (>10m below ground level). The aim is for an open public-private winter garden to span the entire ground level, providing retail space and pedestrian access to Waterloo Station to the east of the site. The building will be formed of three steps, the tallest step (up to 39 storeys) in the north, the middle step (currently 22 storeys) and the lowest step (currently 9 storeys) in the south. Above ground, it is proposed that the south step is separated from the remainder of the building by a party wall. The basement will be connected across the site and three main cores are proposed to serve the building. In addition to the office regions of the building, a gym and a bar / restaurant are being considered for Level 1 and the uppermost level, respectively. The structure of the building will consist of concrete basements and steel frame above ground.  The facade is currently proposed as being 50% glazed. The main aims for the development are a reconciliation of: the above-ground constraints, principally the viewing corridors any daylight / rights to light; the below ground constraints, principally the four London Underground Ltd (LUL) lines that pass beneath the building, and the associated shafts and other tunnels associated with the station and maximisation of the development potential of the site – in terms of building height and massing in a format which provides an optimal layout.

ScopeOfWorks:
Darwin Building. UWE has asked Arup to provide a proposal for conducting a review of the stairwell pressurisation system within the Darwin Building to providing recommendations for ongoing operational and performance requirements.  The possible outcomes of such a review would be:
1. The system does not achieve the required standard and needs upgrading.
2. The system achieves an acceptable standard and should be maintained and operated in its existing state.
3. The system is no longer necessary (there could be a number of reasons for this) and can be decommissioned.
However, it is understood that the system currently achieves a pressure differential of 20Pa, which falls short of the required pressure differential of 40Pa which was the design criterion at the time of installation as advised by UWE.  Therefore, unless a review is conducted to determine the current requirements of the system, the only possible outcome will be that the system does not achieve the required standard and needs upgrading.
Therefore, we recommended that Arup be appointed to:
• Review any available documentation to determine why the system was originally required.
• We have been advised by UWE that there is no fire strategy or risk assessment for the building. Therefore we need to determine the fire strategy for the building and then carry out a risk assessment to determine the performance requirements (if any) of the pressurisation system as a component of the overall fire strategy. 
The objective of the above work would be to develop a fire strategy that reduces the reliance on the pressurisation system and that avoids the need for upgrades to the system.
It should also be noted that the fire strategy forms the first step of the risk assessment process under the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005. This process would also assist UWE in meeting their responsibility under the RRO.
To enable us to achieve this and provide recommendations for the stairwell pressurisation system, we propose the following stages of work.  A staged approach is proposed as it can only be confirmed that subsequent stages are necessary (and will provide value) on completion of the previous stage.  This approach also minimises UWE’s initial fee exposure.
ClientName: University of the West of England - Bristol

ScopeOfService: As above and as per fee proposal
ScopeOfWorks:
Fire engineering services to review and assess the fire hydrant provisions and benefits at the following sites:
• Glenside (18 no.)
• Frenchay ‘newland’
• Bower Ashton (2 no.)
In order to satisfy the brief and prepare a fire hydrant assessment at each of the three sites, we propose the following stages and scope of work; Stage 1: Carry out a site audit at each of the three sites to assess current hydrant provisions, and obtain the following information.
• Review hydrant locations (drawings to be provided by UWE).
• Review dry riser locations (drawings to be provided by UWE).
• Review access routes from hydrants to buildings for fire fighting purposes. In particular the fire vehicle access and requirements for fire hydrants. 
• Review available hydrant data / current system performance (pressure, flow rates, etc) 
We have allowed 3 days work to carry out the above works including one meeting with Estate Staff.
Stage 2: Produce a design note to summarise the hydrant provision at each of the three sites. Each note will contain sketches showing fire vehicle access routes, points of building access for fire and rescue service and indicative hydrant locations. The note will also include the following:
• List hydrant coverage requirements for each building - operational parameters and performance requirements (pressures, flow rates, etc).
• Assess adequacy of hydrant coverage against this requirements taking in to consideration the current use of each building.
• Recommendations/options for building /engineering remedial or upgrade works, in relation to the hydrant systems and assessment of potential alterative (underground) water supplies if required.. 
• Suitable testing and maintenance regime, including frequency and applicable standards.
Stage 3: Present the findings to the Estates Staff at UWE and review the benefits that maybe delivered by hydrant use and entering into an agreement with Avon Fire and Rescue Service for ongoing health checks.
Liaise with Avon Fire and Rescue Service on behalf of UWE to identify hydrant provisions and/or recommendations required as a result of the assessment.
It should be noted that the brief asks for budgetary figures associated with the recommendations / options provided in the final report. This is not typical of the service we provide. Clients typically have a preferred contractor/company that they use for remedial/upgrade works. We have therefore not included for this element of work within our fee.

ScopeOfWorks: Refurbishment of an existing building to a working industrial museum. The Lion Salt Works is the last surviving open salt works in Cheshire. It was built, owned and operated by one family throughout its operational life. The Thompson family had been in the salt business from the eighteenth century, mining rick salt and pumping brine, until the Lion Salt Works closed in 1986. The Lion Salt Works is owned by Chester and Cheshire West Council (C&CW). The Lion Salt Works Trust was formed in 1993 to work with the Council and other bodies to restore this important and unique site, now a Scheduled Ancient Monument. Several existing buildings are located on the site. These include five pan houses, the Lion Inn, pump house, boiler house and manager’s office, brine tank and salt store. These buildings vary in age, construction and condition. The extent of the restoration varies for each building. As part of the project, each building that is accessed by the public was made safe from structural collapse. The design of the museum incorporates the five pan houses and the Lion Inn. The museum allows the public to walk through three of the pan houses to experience and understand the salt making process. Exhibitions are installed in the other pan houses but public access is restricted.

ScopeOfWorks:
The project comprises the refurbishment of the derelict Head Post Office, which are Grade II Listed Buildings dating back to 1893, into a vibrant contemporary Art and Design Facility and home to the Sheffield Institute of Art.

The Post Office vacated the complex in 2001, but sadly very little was done to protect it from vandalism, in particular broken windows and the theft of significant amounts of leadwork from roof flashings / valleys and cornices subsequently left the fabric of the building degrading and saturated, vulnerable to the elements and covered in a thick layer of guano.

Sheffield Hallam had a geographically spread Arts faculty and the desire to find a new home for the Sheffield Institute of Arts. SIA’s space requirement such that all the listed building’s would to be utilised, securing their future and re-use via a sensitive adaptation and comprehensive refurbishment.

To enable the SIA’s tenancy to be secured, a critical element was the repair and making weathertight of the main listed buildings. The decision was made to secure funding for Enabling Phase 1 of the project – through HMRC’s BPRA scheme - to include the provision of new lifts and stair cores and the creation of shell space and flexible space at the upper floors including a mansard extension on the southern wing. Arup were integral in the decision to phase the works – allowing the main larger contract to be de-risked and further investigated during this phase and the SIA tenancy was subsequently secured on the basis of this confident start on the project – this approach ultimately made the scheme viable.

The site is located within a predominantly residential area, approximately 1.1km north of the River Thames and covers an area of approximately 4.7ha abutting the High Speed 1 Channel Tunnel Rail link on its northern boundary. It was identified as one of the top ten stations requiring development to bring it in line with minimum standards for passenger expectations of stations within the Department for Transport's (DfT) ‘Better Railway Stations’ report.  The works are also the result of asset condition and non-compliance assessments, particularly in respect to the dilapidated roof structure, which is life-expired. Fitting within the Northern Hub programme of works, this project is the redevelopment of Manchester Victoria Station in respect to: the external approaches, main station building and existing offices, concourse works, installation of a mezzanine level serving the MEN Arena and (most significantly) a new ETFE roof.  The project ambition is to provide both an immediate and long term affect to the passenger experience, through a phase of regeneration to the surrounding area.

ScopeOfWorks:
The University of Birmingham’s new library is set to transform and reinvigorate the main campus, providing a facility for the 21st century. The space has been designed to meet the changing needs of students, staff, and the wider community which the former 1950s library could no longer meet. The new replacement library comprises circa 16,000m² of floor space over six floors which houses 2,000 study spaces in group, single study, and IT clusters, 15km of shelving, a post-graduate hub, a café and an exhibition space to showcase research at the University. The new library will have an BREEAM ‘Excellent’ rating and will offer a 50 per cent reduction in energy usage compared to the existing library, helping the university to achieve its 20 per cent CO2 reduction target by 2020. We have developed the building structure in a manner that is unobtrusive from the outside but becomes a prominent feature on the inside. Internally, the concrete structure is exposed and, where appropriate, is expressed as an important part of the overall aesthetic. Consequently, attention to detail has been at the heart of our thinking to ensure that the structure enhances the internal feel of the building. The new building has a contextual modern aesthetic, a contemporary but respectful neighbour to the listed Aston Webb buildings. A high level of glazing maximises views in and out, achieving optimum day-lighting to produce the very best study environment possible. Windows are set within a regular framework of stone with brick infill. Glass louvres provide solar shading and add a layer of detail to the elevations. Other materials are aluminium and zinc cladding. The importance of the corner beside the University Centre is emphasised by angled stone columns with brick linings orientated to the landmark University clock tower. 

Contract type: Single stage D&B with novation at end of Stage E (novation under an architectural framework holder) to JCT design and build contract.

ScopeOfWorks: The Liverpool City Region (LCR) Sustainable Energy Action Plan (SEAP) was prepared by Arup for the Merseyside Environmental Advisory Service. Arup completed technical and policy research, consultation and publishing of the action plan. The SEAP sets out the way forward for a single co-ordinated programme to ensure the Liverpool City Region is at the forefront of the transition to a low carbon economy. It provides the strategic direction across the domestic, transport, industrial and commercial sectors to bring investment, jobs, environmental and social benefits to the City Region. The SEAP clearly sets out the opportunities for engagement and participation in this programme. Arup also planned and coordinated the SEAP’s launch at the LCR Energy Summit on 12 July 2012. Sponsored by EON, over 120 senior representatives of business, local authorities and the third sector attended to discuss how the SEAP can help advance the City Region’s ambition to transform itself into a resilient low carbon economy with a sustainable and productive energy sector. The LCR SEAP has now triggered all local authorities in the City Region to join the Covenant of Mayors initiative, identify energy projects needed for a low carbon economy.

JobNameLong: SHEFFIELD HALLAM UNIVERSITY - COLLEGIATE CRESCENT CAMPUS
ScopeOfService: Civil and structural engineering.
ScopeOfWorks: Remodelling of Collegiate Crescent campus including demolition and new build. The Heart of the Campus project was conceived by Sheffield Hallam University to provide a cohesive hub and focal point to their Collegiate Crescent campus. The brief required a feature building, sensitive to its surroundings and with a core of collaborative facilities. The previous buildings on the site included a 1960’s residential tower and series of segregated single storey buildings split over 7 levels across the sloping site, providing a disjointed facility which provided a physical barrier between the two halves of the campus site. In developing a solution for this complex site, the team worked on a building that has a clean and sharp aesthetic, in contrast to the complexity of the constraints of the topography and the four existing buildings that the development ties into. The structure needed to act as the coordinating element within the design, linking the spatial and aesthetic strategies, incorporating these constraints within the form of the structure in a natural, unforced manner. The building itself is multi-purpose with communal teaching, lecture theatres and hub spaces at ground floor and then specific department offices and administration on the upper floors, all flowing around the central feature atrium.

We added value to the project by using our expertise in retrofitting services into old and historic structures, and most importantly collaborating between the Arup Structures and MEP teams in the understanding of the consequences of modifying the existing fabric to accommodate modern services. Provided input through to construction for the refurbishment works to a loadbearing masonry building with internal cast iron column supporting steel beams and timber floors. New openings were formed in the existing floors and walls to transform the existing building. Working closely with the contractor and architect helped to develop the scheme on time and within budget to upgrade and regenerate the existing building.
ScopeOfWorks:
The Symington Building in Market Harborough has been a focal point for the town for well over a hundred years ever since the Symington family started a corset factory on the site. The Victorian Grade II listed building now houses Harborough District Council’s offices, an integrated library and museum as well as shops and local businesses. It has recently undergone major refurbishment works to upgrade the entire building with a larger library, enhanced museum, modern offices and new retail units. 

Arup provided civil, structural and fire engineering services from design through to construction for the refurbishment works which involved forming new openings in the existing floors and walls to transform the existing building. 
The Victorian building was constructed at the end of the 19th century for R & WH Symington and was originally used as a corset factory, which at the time dominated the town centre and was a major employer. The original building had been constructed in 1889 and was then extended shortly afterwards in 1894, with a further extension in 1929. 

The four storey building is L-shaped on plan and is clad with red brickwork and has a slate pitched roof. The building has a tower at the corner facing towards the town centre, and the façade on each elevation has a regular rhythm of large single glazed crittal windows, between brick pilasters. The construction typically consists of load bearing perimeter solid masonry, with a single line of internal wrought iron circular columns supporting wrought iron beams and timber floor joists. The 1929 extension consists of a jack-arched floor and also incorporates a single storey passageway on the front elevation which passes under the building at ground level. For all ages of the building, the third floor is partly within the roof void, with the underside of the existing timber cruck roof structure exposed at this level. 
The existing building was considered to be poorly configured, with numerous internal walls having been added over the years. It had underused internal spaces, performed poorly in the summer and winter, and a number of defects had occurred and was in need of repair. 
The entire building has now been revitalised with spaces that have been completely remodelled and upgraded to accommodate offices for the council’s headquarters, a significantly larger library, enhanced museum, and new retail units. A new atrium space has also been created by removing part of the original structure and floor plate. Detailed assessments were carried out of the existing structure to justify the new loading from the different uses. Loadbearing walls were removed at some locations, and therefore it was necessary to assess the capacity of the existing masonry structure to ensure that it was capable to carrying the loading from the modified load path. A new atrium space has been created by carefully removing part of the existing structure and floor plate at first floor. It was important to fully understand the structural system in this area and the investigation works that were carried out avoided the need for significant strengthening of the existing iron columns and beams. 

The existing entrance canopy was also found to be in a poor condition with numerous timber members showing signs of decay. This has been carefully repaired and given a new lease of life. 

Replacing the existing services and inserting new systems within the historic fabric were complicated challenges, requiring detailed investigation and close co-ordination between the structural and services team members. It was important to establish and agree some basic principles to help develop the servicing strategy, for example general setting out restrictions for vertical and horizontal holes to limit stress increases with additional constraints around door openings and in the zones where the brick walls support the floor beams

ScopeOfWorks: Sheffield’s Future Cities Demonstrator Project will increase the availability of low carbon heat and provide disadvantaged areas of the City with access to affordable, high speed internet connectivity. By integrating heat and digital infrastructure the City will realise significant benefits and illustrate how they can be replicated in other cities and urban areas across the UK. The project will install the largest community scale Wi-Fi network in the country to collect real-time data from 6,000 smart heat meters whilst providing free internet access to 10,000 disadvantaged households providing choice and access to a wider range of services. In addition, 30 independent district heating schemes will be integrated into the main city centre network to allow 2,100 homes to take advantage of the near-zero carbon heat being provided by a new biomass power station connected to the main network using private sector funding. The project will provide economic benefits by building on Sheffield’s base of small and medium enterprises and strong presence in the Creative & Digital Industries sector. Socio-economic benefits include the social, financial, educational and employment opportunities afforded by digital inclusion along with reductions in fuel poverty and improvements in local air quality. The environmental benefits include a direct 7,000 tonne per annum reduction in carbon emissions. The project has been designed to be innovative yet achievable, addressing some of the key challenges facing the UK. It is deliberately designed to be scalable and repeatable. Other cities will be able to directly apply the lessons learnt from the project to help their own transition to a Future City

ScopeOfService: Structural, mechanical, electrical, public health and facades (based on part charitable contribution as agreed with Matthew Lovell and John Turzynski).
ScopeOfWorks:
New Maggie's centre in London by Steven Holl at Barts hospital.

The latest Maggie’s Centre provides a luminous counterpoint to the historic buildings of St Bartholomew’s, London’s oldest hospital. Maggie’s pioneering approach provides emotional, practical and social support to cancer sufferers and their families, using highly considered architecture to create beneficial environments.

Steven Holl’s strongly graphic vision was inspired by medieval neume musical notation, neume appropriately meaning ‘vital force’. His 'three vessel' concept layers a perforated concrete wrapping structure, cloaked within a curved translucent façade and housing a third, bamboo lined interior. Designed to exude light and calm, its openness allows natural light to wash over the floors and walls.

The complex sculptural concrete frame features large voids, branching verticals and curved corners. To create a globally stable structure, we rationalised its geometry, using a BIM model to conduct FE analysis. The open, curved staircase was formed monolithically within the concrete frame, point connected to the concrete branches from which it cantilevers.

Recreating Holl’s trademark watercolour designs with a hard material such as glass resulted in a world-first for cladding, using light-diffusing Okalux glass in curved geometry. The concept pushed the tolerances of curved glass, with flat, cylindrically curved and J-shaped double glazed units. This was further complicated by the embedded coloured swathes which also posed a risk of thermal breakage.To deliver the combined structural and thermal performance of the glass, we developed a bespoke approach using the latest in digital design and analysis.

Maggie’s provide a unique approach to holistic cancer support and the Arup team is immensely proud to have helped realise the latest centre. (Buildings Yearbook Entry 2018).
